The Telegraph - Calcutta : Opinion

 Thursday, July 21, 2005 

 GEARING UP FOR AN EMERGENCY

 DOCUMENT

 Extracts from the WHO?s revised international health regulations, adopted at the World Health Assembly, May 16, 2005 

 Article 48 The Director General shall establish an Emergency Committee...[to] provide its views on: 

 (a) whether an event constitutes a public health emergency of international concern; 

 (b) the termination of a public health emergency of international concern; and 

 (c) the proposed issuance, modification, extension or termination of temporary recommendations.... 

 Article 50 

 1. The Director General shall establish a Review Committee, which shall... 

 (a) make technical recommendations to the Director General regarding amendments to these Regulations; 

 (b) provide technical advice to the Director General with respect to standing recommendations, and any modifications or termination thereof; 

 (c) provide technical advice to the Director General on any matter.... 

 Article 53....

 The Director General shall communicate the Review Committee?s views and advice to the Health Assembly; The Director-General shall communicate to States Parties any standing recommendation...

 Article 54 

 States Parties and the Director General shall report to the Health Assembly on the implementation of these Regulations...The Health Assembly shall periodically review the functioning of these Regulations...The first such review shall take place no later than five years after the entry into force of these Regulations. 

 WHO shall periodically conduct studies to review and evaluate the functioning of Annex 2. The first such review shall commence no later than one year after the entry into force of these Regulations. 

 The results of such reviews shall be submitted to the Health Assembly for its consideration. 

 Article 55... 

 Amendments to these Regulations adopted by the Health Assembly shall come into force for all States Parties on the same terms, and subject to the same rights and obligations, as provided for in Article 22 of the Constitution of WHO and Articles 59 to 64 of these Regulations. 

 Article 56 

 In the event of a dispute between two or more States Parties concerning the interpretation or application of these Regulations, the States Parties concerned shall seek in the first instance to settle the dispute through negotiation or any other peaceful means of their own choice, including good offices, mediation or conciliation. Failure to reach agreement shall not absolve the parties to the dispute from the responsibility of continuing to seek to resolve it. 

 In the event of a dispute between WHO and one or more States Parties concerning the interpretation or application of these Regulations, the matter shall be submitted to the Health Assembly. 

 Article 57 

 States Parties recognize that the IHR and other relevant international agreements should be interpreted so as to be compatible... 

 Subject to paragraph 1 of this Article, nothing in these Regulations shall prevent States Parties having certain interests in common owing to their health, geographical, social or economic conditions, from concluding special treaties or arrangements in order to facilitate the application of these Regulations... 

 Article 59...

 These Regulations shall enter into force 24 months after the date of notification referred to in paragraph 1 of this Article... 

 TO BE CONCLUDED




